Dropdown activation is already tied to the focusNode and textEditingController within the `RawAutocomplete` widget.  Adding the ability to control adds a lot to the possible things that can be done...

This is some of the relevant (existing) code from `RawAutocomplete`:
```dart
  bool get _canShowOptionsView => _focusNode.hasFocus && _selection == null && _options.isNotEmpty;

  void _updateOptionsViewVisibility() {
    if (_canShowOptionsView) {
      _optionsViewController.show();
    } else {
      _optionsViewController.hide();
    }
  }

  // Called when _textEditingController changes.
  Future<void> _onChangedField() async {
    final TextEditingValue value = _textEditingController.value;
    final Iterable<T> options = await widget.optionsBuilder(value);
    _options = options;
    _updateHighlight(_highlightedOptionIndex.value);
    final T? selection = _selection;
    if (selection != null && value.text != widget.displayStringForOption(selection)) {
      _selection = null;
    }

    // Make sure the options are no longer hidden if the content of the field
    // changes (ignore selection changes).
    if (value.text != _lastFieldText) {
      _lastFieldText = value.text;
      _updateOptionsViewVisibility();
    }
  }
```

Simply doing a textEditController.notifyListeners() will trigger the listeners (no *actual* change is required in the text of the textEditController).
You could trigger the dropdown from another button by doing this:
1) foucsNode.requestFocus();
2) textEditController.notifyListeners(),
    [this will trigger a optionsBuilder callback]
3) then in the optionsBuilder callback we return a non-empty list (non empty list will make the options dropdown appear, or an empty list will make the options dropdown disappear)

[Refer  `_canShowOptionsView` and `_onChangedField` in the code above to see how this will trigger showing/hiding the options dropdown]

You would place/wrap tap listeners on whichever widgets you wanted to be able to do this (for example on the dropdown chevron).  You could place shortcut listeners higher up in the page and capture Ctrl-DownArrow shortcuts and then see whats focused and do the above to trigger the dropdown...
You could also place listeners on focusNode so that you could control onFocus behaviors. 

Using this method of controlling the options dropdown visibility to triggering/and controlling the # of options in the options list should all complete control of when the options list appears/disappears.

I understand that being able to control the shortcut and intent list that `RawAutocomplete` create might be more versatile and ideal, but I don't think that level of change, to a lower level widget in the Flutter framework, would not be an easy change to get through the approval process.  (this change may even be difficult to get through and it is just passing 2 arguments through to `RawAutocomplete`).

I try and make some time to play with making an example proof of concept.

Some experiments on this. (More details https://github.com/flutter/flutter/issues/78031#issuecomment-864400962)

It looks like a font issue. Without specifying any style to the `TextField`, it applies Roboto fonts by default, but the `textarea` element created as shadow applies an apple font on Safari by default, which causes them out of sync.

Adding Roboto fonts to `pubspec.yaml` and applying them to the `TextField` won't fix. Although the font is properly applied to the shadow `textarea` element, it's not taking any effect.

![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/39660295/122660074-bc633680-d1b0-11eb-8e1b-1755b2fda5c0.png)

It seems that we have the font downloaded but it's not recognised by Safari. We add Roboto fonts CSS to the template index.html and finally see the `textarea` perfectly overlaps with the flutter `TextField`.

