This happens on iOS only, and at the moment iOS doesn’t support autofill for credit cards (even though there is a special content type for such fields). So, it doesn’t make sense to keep these values in the same text field. You can do something like this:

```dart
TextField(
    // Not supported on iOS
    autofillHints: AppPlatform.isIOS ? [] : [AutofillHints.creditCardNumber],
    keyboardType: TextInputType.number,
    // ...
);
```

Regarding the root issue, I found out that when iOS has an input with `.creditCardNumber` and a non-default `returnKeyType` (`textInputAction` in Flutter), it falls back to the alphanumeric keyboard. I have no idea why the engine uses `UIReturnKeyDone` by default, but another workaround in Flutter is to set `textInputAction: TextInputAction.unspecified` in the text input.

```dart
TextField(
    autofillHints: [AutofillHints.creditCardNumber],
    keyboardType: TextInputType.number,
    textInputAction: TextInputAction.unspecified,
    // ...
);
```

